That’s a great question! If you’re interested in creating a digital gallery for your cycling event images, you can leverage the FormData object to handle image uploads from a form and then display them online. Here’s a detailed breakdown of how you might approach this:

1. Understanding FormData: The FormData object in JavaScript allows you to easily compile a set of key/value pairs to send using Ajax (with the fetch API or XMLHttpRequest). In your case, you’d be using it to gather image files selected by the user.

2. Setting Up the HTML Form: Create an HTML form with an input element of type=file. For handling multiple images, you can use the multiple attribute. This is what your form might look like:

   •  <form id='uploadForm' enctype='multipart/form-data'>
   •      <input type='file' id='imageInput' name='cyclingImages' accept='image/*' multiple />
   •      <button type='submit'>Upload Images</button>
   •  </form>

3. Using JavaScript to Collect Files: When the form is submitted, prevent the default behavior and create a new FormData object. Then, loop through each selected file and append it to FormData:

   •  const formElement = document.getElementById('uploadForm');
   •  formElement.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
   •      e.preventDefault();  // Prevent form from submitting in the traditional way
   •      const fileInput = document.getElementById('imageInput');
   •      const files = fileInput.files;
   •      const formData = new FormData();

   •      for (let i = 0; i < files.length; i++) {
   •          formData.append('cyclingImages[]', files[i]);
   •      }

   •      // Now you can send formData to your server using fetch or another Ajax method
   •      // fetch('/path-to-upload', { method: 'POST', body: formData })
   •  });

4. Sending the Data to a Server: If you don’t have a large server backend yet, you could use a service or a lightweight backend where you upload the images and store information about them. The server would then respond with either the URLs or some confirmation of stored files.

5. Displaying the Digital Gallery: Once the images are uploaded and stored, you can retrieve the image URLs from your server and dynamically insert them into your webpage as part of a gallery. You might, for example, create an image grid that mimics the layout of a wall display. Here’s a simple idea:

   •  <div id='gallery'></div>

   •  Fetch the gallery images using JavaScript and then for each URL, create an <img> element, then append it to the gallery div. This creates a dynamic, online poster wall that you can customize with your own styles and even add effects for a more interactive experience.

6. Additional Enhancements: 
   •  You can add loaders or progress bars during uploads for better user experience.
   •  Implement error handling to manage any upload issues.
   •  If you’re interested in more interactivity, libraries like Masonry or CSS Grids can help you style the gallery so that your digital ‘race posters’ are laid out attractively.

Even if you don’t have physical space for your cycling paraphernalia, a digital solution lets you store, share, and enjoy your racing memories without cluttering your living area. It’s a flexible way to keep your passions showcased and accessible anywhere, anytime.

I hope this detailed explanation clarifies how you can use FormData to build your digital gallery and turns the challenge of limited physical space into an opportunity for a creative online solution!

